    <h2>What Is a Healthy Weight for a 5'7" man?</h2>
    <p>A man who is 5 feet 7 inches has a healthy weight range of <strong>118–159 lb (54–72 kg)</strong> according to standard BMI guidelines (BMI 18.5–24.9). This range is based on population-level research linking body weight to health outcomes including cardiovascular disease, type 2 diabetes, and all-cause mortality.</p>
    <p>The four established ideal weight formulas (Devine, Robinson, Miller, and Hamwi) give a single target weight rather than a range. For a 5'7" man, these formulas average out to approximately <strong>146 lb (66.1 kg)</strong>. This sits comfortably within the BMI healthy range and can serve as a useful personal target.</p>
    <div class="callout"><p>💡 <strong>Quick check:</strong> If you are a man at 5'7" and your weight is between 118–159 lb (54–72 kg), your BMI is in the healthy range. Use our <a href="bmi-calculator.html">BMI calculator</a> to get your exact number.</p></div>

    <h2>Asian BMI Standard</h2>
    <p>If you are of Asian descent, the WHO recommends a lower healthy BMI ceiling of 22.9 (rather than 24.9) because Asian populations develop metabolic health risks at lower BMI values. For a 5'7" man, the Asian-standard healthy weight range is <strong>118–146 lb (54–66 kg)</strong>. See our <a href="asian-bmi-calculator.html">Asian BMI Calculator</a> for a full assessment.</p>

    <h2>Why the Healthy Range Varies by Formula</h2>
    <p>Each ideal weight formula was developed for a specific clinical purpose:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Devine (1974)</strong> — originally developed to estimate drug dosing for patients. Still widely used in pharmacology.</li>
      <li><strong>Robinson (1983)</strong> — a refinement of Devine based on broader population data.</li>
      <li><strong>Miller (1983)</strong> — tends to give slightly higher estimates, particularly for taller individuals.</li>
      <li><strong>Hamwi (1964)</strong> — one of the oldest formulas, used in clinical dietetics.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>None of these formulas accounts for body composition, muscle mass, or bone density. A muscular athlete and a sedentary man of the same height will have the same "ideal weight" by formula — but very different body fat percentages. For a fuller picture, use our <a href="body-fat.html">Body Fat Calculator</a> alongside this guide.</p>

    <h2>Tips for Reaching a Healthy Weight</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Calculate your daily calorie needs with the <a href="calorie-calculator.html">Calorie Calculator</a> and aim for a moderate deficit (300–500 kcal/day) if you want to lose weight</li>
      <li>Prioritise protein (1.6–2.2 g per kg of body weight) to preserve muscle while losing fat — see our <a href="high-protein-foods.html">high-protein foods guide</a></li>
      <li>Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate aerobic activity per week alongside 2 strength sessions</li>
      <li>Track progress by how your clothes fit and your energy levels, not just the scale</li>
    </ul>

